column6: Communities dominated by low, woody, self supporting, multi-5stemmed plants, branching at or near the ground, between 0.2 and 2 m in height. Total tree cover < 0.1 Typical examples are low Fynbos, Karoo and Lesotho (alpine) communities.
Communities dominated by low, non-woody, non-grass like plants, between 0.2 and 2 m in height. Total tree cover < 0.1  Typical examples are found in Namaqualand or ?weed? dominated degraded areas.
Open land, cleared of vegetation (i.e. trees / bushes), and often covered in a new road network, in preparation for the development of new urban development.

As above, except ?. Planted grassland, containing either indigenous or exotic species, growing under man-managed (including irrigated) conditions for grazing, hay or turf production, recreation (i.e. golf) etc

Natural or artificial areas where the water level is permanently or temporarily at (or very near) the land surface, typically covered in either herbaceous or woody vegetation cover. The category includes fresh, brakish and salt-water conditions. Examples include pans (with non-permanent water cover), and reed-marsh or papyrus-swamp. Dry pans are included in this category unless they are permanently dry.

Natural areas of exposed sand, soil or rock with no, or very little vegetation cover during any time of the year, (excluding agricultural fields with no crop cover, and open cast mines and quarries). Examples would include rock outcrops, beach sand, and dry riverbed material.
Formal township areas with limited gardens and high to medium housing densities. Includes both permanent and semi-permanent structures.
Densely wooded areas, where the tree canopy exceeds 70 % cover, and 30 m height. Essentially indigenous species growing under natural or semi-natural conditions.

All areas of grassland with < 10% tree and/or shrub canopy cover, and >0.1% total vegetation cover. Dominated by grass-like, non-woody, rooted herbaceous plants. Essentially indigenous species growing under natural or semi-natural conditions.
Informal residential areas with very high housing densities. Street patterns generally not visible.
Includes both residential and agricultural smallholdings/plots around the urban periphery, containing individual buildings or building clusters with very low building densities.
Small rural clusters and areas that contains both formal and informal housing structures.
Includes all road structures.
Vegetation relating to sports fields, etc.
All areas that include bushveld, fynbos, herbland, grassland, wetland and crops are classified as low vegetation.
All forest, woodlands and plantations are classified as high vegetation.  These areas generally have a dense canopy cover of > 70%.  Includes urban trees.
Open areas with little or no vegetation. Parking lots, mine dumps, quarries, show grounds, school grounds, barren land etc.
Areas of permanent or near permanent water - whether natural or man-made, flowing or static. Includes rivers, dams, pans, lakes and the ocean.
Individual or groups of very tall, permanent structures, with building heights over 50m (> 8 floors) high.   Includes CBD ?skyscrapers?, silos and cooling towers.

Individual or groups of very tall, permanent structures with building heights generally lower than 50m (5-8 floors) high. Generally high building density per urban block.  Main commercial areas, large city centers and CBD.
Individual or groups of permanent structures generally between 3-5 floors high. High building density per urban block, smaller commercial areas and city centers.
Individual or groups of permanent structures generally between 2-3 floors high. High building density per urban block.  Includes school buildings.

Individual or groups of permanent structures generally between 2-5 floors high with large building footprints.   Includes university/technicon campuses, office complexes, large shopping centers and airport terminal buildings.
Individual permanent structure with footprints typically 150 m x 150 m and an average height of generally more than 20 m.  National, regional and university sport stadiums.

Individual or groups of permanent structures used for manufacture, industrial processing or transport related activities.  Individual structures more than 1 200 sqm (30 x 40 m) and less than 4 500 sqm area, with less than 25 m height.
Individual or groups of permanent structures used for manufacture, transport or commercial/warehouse activities.  Individual structures typically > 4 500 sqm area, with < 25 m height.
Areas of dense residential townhouses and cluster housing with structures 1-3 floors high.
Formal residential areas generally with gardens and medium to low housing densities.

Non-residential areas with major technology, manufacturing or transport related infrastructure. Examples would include light manufacturing units, warehouse dominated business development centres, and small airports (i.e. Lanseria). Also includes similar structures such as farm-based pig and battery hen breeding units.
Active or non-active underground or sub-surface based mining activities. Category includes all associated surface infrastructure etc

Primarily non-vegetated, exposed mining  (and heavy industry) extraction or waste material. Major areas of managed vegetation re-habilitation on these sites can be mapped according to the appropriate vegetation category.

All areas of systematically planted, man-managed tree resources, composed of primarily exotic species (including hybrids). Category includes both young and mature plantations that have been established for commercial timber production, seedling trials and woodlot / windbreaks of sufficient size to be identifiable on satellite imagery. Excludes all non-timber based plantations such as tea, sisal, citrus, nut crops etc.

All areas of systematically planted, man-managed tree resources, composed of primarily exotic species (including hybrids). Category includes both young and mature plantations that have been established for commercial timber production, seedling trials and woodlot / windbreaks of sufficient size to be identifiable on satellite imagery. Excludes all non-timber based plantations such as tea, sisal, citrus, nut crops etc.

All areas of systematically planted, man-managed tree resources, composed of primarily exotic species (including hybrids). Category includes both young and mature plantations that have been established for commercial timber production, seedling trials and woodlot / windbreaks of sufficient size to be identifiable on satellite imagery. Excludes all non-timber based plantations such as tea, sisal, citrus, nut crops etc.

Areas of (generally permanent) open water. The category includes both natural and man-made waterbodies, which are either static or flowing, and fresh, brakish and salt-water conditions. This category includes features such as rivers, major reservoirs, farm-level irrigation dams, permanent pans, lakes and lagoons.

Non-vegetated areas or areas of very little vegetation cover in comparison to the surrounding natural vegetation, that are primarily the result of active gully erosion processes. Typically located in association with areas of poor grassland cover along existing streamlines and or on slightly steeper slopes than sheet erosion areas i.e. greater than 6 degree slope. In some areas the full extent of donga activity may be obscured by either overhanging adjacent bushes, encroaching thorn bush, or, in the case of more stable dongas, by bush or grass cover along the actual streamline.

Non-vegetated areas or areas of very little vegetation cover in comparison to the surrounding natural vegetation, that are primarily the result of active sheet erosion processes. Typically located in association with areas of severe donga erosion and  or poor grassland cover i.e. low image NDVI rating. In some areas the full extent of this process may be obscured by encroaching bush. Typically located on slopes less than or equal to 6 degrees.

Permanent or near-permanent, man-induced areas of very low vegetation cover i.e. removal of tree, bush, or herbaceous cover in comparison to the surrounding natural vegetation cover. Typically associated with subsistence level agriculture and rural population centres, where overgrazing of livestock and or wood-resource removal has been locally excessive. Often associated with severe soil erosion problems.

Permanent or near-permanent, man-induced areas of very low vegetation cover i.e. removal of tree, bush, or herbaceous cover in comparison to the surrounding natural vegetation cover. Typically associated with subsistence level agriculture and rural population centres, where overgrazing of livestock and or wood-resource removal has been locally excessive. Often associated with severe soil erosion problems.

Permanent or near-permanent, man-induced areas of very low vegetation cover i.e. removal of tree, bush, or herbaceous cover in comparison to the surrounding natural vegetation cover. Typically associated with subsistence level agriculture and rural population centres, where overgrazing of livestock and or wood-resource removal has been locally excessive. Often associated with severe soil erosion problems.

Permanent or near-permanent, man-induced areas of very low vegetation cover i.e. removal of tree, bush, or herbaceous cover in comparison to the surrounding natural vegetation cover. Typically associated with subsistence level agriculture and rural population centres, where overgrazing of livestock and or wood-resource removal has been locally excessive. Often associated with severe soil erosion problems.

Permanent or near-permanent, man-induced areas of very low vegetation cover i.e. removal of tree, bush, or herbaceous cover in comparison to the surrounding natural vegetation cover. Typically associated with subsistence level agriculture and rural population centres, where overgrazing of livestock and or wood-resource removal has been locally excessive. Often associated with severe soil erosion problems.

Densely wooded areas, where the tree and/or bush canopy exceeds 70 % cover, but canopy height is < 30m. Essentially indigenous species growing under natural or semi-natural conditions. Includes plantations, natural forests and dense natural bushveld
Non-permanent shack type dwellings (i.e. tin, cardboard, wood etc) typically established on an informal, ad hoc basis, on non-serviced sites. Typically high building densities

Non-residential, non-industrial sites or complexes associated with educational (i.e. schools, universities), business development centres such as industrial ?techno-parks?, and / or social services (i.e. hospitals), often consisting of a concentration of multi-level buildings (Note : only mapped if clearly identifiable, otherwise included within ?commercial / mercantile? or ?suburban? categories.

Non-residential areas with major industrial (i.e. manufacture and/or processing of goods and products) or transport related infrastructure. Examples would include power stations, steel mills, dockyards, train stations and airports (i.e. Johannesburg).

Active or non-active surface-based mining activities. Includes both hardrock or sand quarry extraction sites, and opencast mining sites i.e. coal.  Category includes all associated surface infrastructure.

Permanent residential structures, either single or multi-level, located within new or well-established residential areas, i.e. ?garden-suburbs?, (often refers to ?middle-class? and ?upper class? residential areas). Includes both low and high building densities.

Non-residential structures used for manufacture, technology, transport or commercial / warehouse activities. Individual structures > 1200 m² (30x40 m), and < 4500 m² area, with < 25 m height. Local building densities can be high, although primary access roads typically > 20 m wide.

Permanent or near-permanent residential areas, which are too small to subdivide into more specific urban / built-up areas. Identifiable by the local high building density and associated infrastructure. Includes towns, villages, and where applicable, the central nucleus of more open, rural clusters.
Permanent residential structures, consisting mainly of 3 or more levels (often up to 10), resulting in a concentration of mid-to-high rise building, for example Hillbrow (Jhb) or Sunnyside (Pta).
mixed residential

Permanent (i.e. brick etc) structures (predominately single level), usually located on serviced sites within former black residential areas, laid out in a organised, pre-planned manner. Includes both low and high building densities.

Permanent / semi-permanent shack type dwellings (i.e. corrugated tin structures) laid out and established in an organised, pre-planned manner on both serviced and non-serviced sites. Includes both low and high building densities

Areas of clustered rural dwellings (i.e. kraals) whose structural density is too low to be classified as a formal village, but are of sufficient level to be easily identifiable as such on satellite imagery. Small scale cultivation / garden plots often form a major spatial component, and are located amongst the residential structures.
Permanent residential structures, typically located in formal township districts, consisting mainly of 1 or 2 levels in concentrated block-like structures.

Non-residential areas used primarily for the conduct of commerce and other mercantile business, typically located in the central business district (CBD). Often consisting of a concentration of multi-level buildings, but also includes small commercial zones (i.e. spaza shops) within former black townships.

Both formal and informal ‘township’ areas with high building densities, with open areas and non-primary access routes typically equal to or smaller than individual structures. Open areas and garden plots are covered with a dense tree and bush canopy cover. Structures can be permanent (e.g brick) and semi-permanent shack type dwellings (e.g. corrugated tin) of a single level laid out in an organized, pre-planned manner on both serviced and non-serviced sites or non-permanent shack-type dwellings (e.g. tin, cardboard, wood) typically established on an informal, ad hoc basis on non-serviced sites.
As above, except for : Open areas non-wooded and are either non-vegetated or grass covered.

Non-residential structures used for manufacture, industrial processing or transport related activities. Large structures typically >4500 m² (e.g. 90x50 m), and <25 m height. Local building densities can be high, although primary access roads typically >20 m wide.
Mining waste dumps and tailings, typically > 30 m in height made by mining and other man made activities

Land which has been ploughed and or prepared for the raising of crops excluding timber production. Unless otherwise stated includes areas currently under crop fallow land and land being prepared for planting. Class boundaries are broadly defined to encompass the main areas of agricultural activity and are not defined on exact field boundaries. As such all sub-classes may include small inter-field cover types e.g. hedges grass strips small windbreaks as well as farm infrastructure Commercial  characterised by large uniform well managed field units i.e.   50 ha with the aim of supplying both regional national and export markets. Often highly mechanised.

All wooded areas with a tree canopy > 70 %. A multi-strata community, with interlocking canopies, composed of canopy, sub-canopy, shrub and herb layers. The canopy is composed mainly of self-supporting, single stemmed, woody plants > 5 metres in height. Essentially indigenous species, growing under natural or semi-natural conditions (although it may include some areas of self-seeded exotic species). Excludes planted forests (and woodlots)

All areas of systematically planted, man-managed tree resources, composed of primarily exotic species (including hybrids). Category includes both young and mature plantations that have been established for commercial timber production, seedling trials and woodlot / windbreaks of sufficient size to be identifiable on satellite imagery. Excludes all non-timber based plantations such as tea, sisal, citrus, nut crops etc
Tall, permanent buildings with high building density (i.e. “skyscrapers”) More than 8 floors
Tall permanent buildings with high building density per urban block. (‘high building density’ defined as total building footprint >80% of total ground area) and typically 5-8 floors.
Groups of permanent structures subdivided by non-vegetated, primary roads and streets. Structures are typically 3 – 5 floors
Buildings with high unit density per urban block, subdivided by non-vegetated, primary roads and streets. Typically 2-3 floors and include suburban structures such as townhouses.

Formal residential areas with medium building density, where structures dominate per unit area compared to gardens and open areas, covering 50 – 80% of land area. Structures are generally houses with 1 – 2 floors. Gardens with trees and bushes make up the rest of available land area.  Individual plots typically < 900m² (30 x 30 m)
As above, except for  : gardens, open areas and streets have a low tree and bush cover and are primarily grass-covered.

Formal residential areas with low building density, where gardens and open space dominate per unit area compared to structures and open areas covering 50 – 80% of land area. Structures are generally houses with 1 – 2 floors. Individual plots typically < 900m² (30 x 30 m)
As above, except for : Gardens, open areas and streets have a low tree and bush canopy cover and are primarily grass-covered.

Bush and low tree dominated areas, where the canopy cover is 40 - 70 % and canopy height 3 - 5m. Essentially indigenous species growing under natural or semi-natural conditions. Include open canopy woodland and bushveld, young exotic tree plantations and citrus plantations.

Areas of sparse tree and bush cover, where the total canopy cover is 10 – 40 %. A very open vegetation community, typically with a low grassland  background. Local examples include sparse bushveld, widely distributed bush-clumps, and  wooded grassland.

Mostly open areas, but patches of slightly higher vegetation and / or building structures. Includes areas of scattered rural dwellings (traditional kraals),  small scale subsistence cultivation, taller (>0.75m) commercial crops (eg maize, vineyards), sparse shack settlements, or urban park areas. Isolated individual buildings or building clusters can be included if too small for other class types.

Open areas with few or no tall building or vegetation features. Includes all low vegetation covers < 0.75 m, such as natural or man-managed grasslands, low heathland (i.e. karoo, fynbos), and cultivated areas with crops < 0. 75m (incl. fallow fields), irrespective of land-use management practices. Also includes non-vegetated areas such as quarries and open cast mines, dry pans, and tidal mudflats etc.
Areas of permanently dry, exposed sand, rock or soil, with no vegetation cover during any time of the year, irrespective of size or extent. Includes dunes, beaches, riverine sand etc.
Areas of permanent, or near permanent open water. Includes both static, flowing and tidal waterbodies.

Natural or artificially vegetated areas (typically < 2 m height), where the water level is permanently or temporarily at (or very near) the land surface. Includes both vleis, pans, wetlands and marshes (including coastal saltmarsh)

All wooded areas with a tree canopy between 10 - 70%. A broad sparse - open ? closed canopy community, typically consisting of a single tree canopy layer and a herb (grass) layer. The canopy is composed mainly of self-supporting, single stemmed, woody plants > 5 metres in height. Essentially indigenous species, growing under natural or semi-natural conditions (although it may include some areas of self-seeded exotic species). Excludes planted forests (and woodlots). Canopy cover density classes may be mapped if desired, based on sparse (< 40%), open (40 ? 70 %), and closed (> 70 %).

Communities typically composed of tall, woody, self-supporting, single or multi-stemmed plants (branching at or near the ground), with, in most cases no clearly definable structure. Total canopy cover is greater than 10%, with canopy heights between 2 ? 5 metres. Essentially indigenous species, growing under natural or semi-natural conditions (although it may include some areas of self-seeded exotic species, especially along riparian zones). Presence of alien exotic species can be modelled spatially using broad principles of unlikely structural / temporal occurrences within a given vegetation biome or region. Dense bush encroachment would be included in this category.

All areas of systematically planted, man-managed tree resources, composed of primarily exotic species (including hybrids). Category includes both young and mature plantations that have been established for commercial timber production, seedling trials and woodlot / windbreaks of sufficient size to be identifiable on satellite imagery. Excludes all non-timber based plantations such as tea, sisal, citrus, nut crops etc

A generic urban class, essentially comprising all formal built-up areas, in which people reside on a permanent or near-permanent basis, identifiable by the high density of residential and associated infrastructure. Includes both towns, villages, and where applicable, the central nucleus of more open, rural clusters. This class should be used if it is not possible to identify more industrial and transportation land-uses. Low-density smallholdings frequently located on the urban / peri-urban fringe should be mapped as a separate smallholding sub-classes, subdivided by the appropriate (level I) background vegetation type. If visible, individual farm units are to be mapped as isolated urban / built-up units (if no other class is applicable). Specific urban / built-up sub-classes as listed below ? in such cases it could include residential, commercial,
